{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> σκορπί-ος</b>, ὁ, <br /> <b>scorpion</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 169, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthydemus” 290a, “Sammelb.” 1267.7 (1st c.AD), etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σ. ὁ χερσαῖος[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" (see. below 11) 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 555a23: proverbial, ὑπὸ παντὶ λίθῳ σκορπίον φυλάσσεο 5th c.BC: Praxilla Lyrica 4; ἐν παντὶ σ. φρουρεῖ λίθῳ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 37 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also σκορπίον ὀκτώπουν ἐγείρεις 'let sleeping dogs lie', [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.AD(?): Hesychius Legal icographus; ὥσπερ ἔχις ἢ σ. ἠρκὼς τὸ κέντρον 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 25.52. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> a sea-fish, probably <b>Scorpaena scrofa</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 261.9, Diocl.fragment 135, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 508b17, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.977f\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; used (like the <b>mugilis</b> in Catull.15.19, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD: Juvenalis, D. Junius Poeta Latinus 10.317) to punish adulterers, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Comicus 173.21; uncertain meaning in LXX.1Ki.12.11. \">LXX+5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>scorpion furze, Genista acanthoclada</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 6.1.3, 6.4.1. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> <b>scorpion root, Doronicum caucasicum</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 9.13.6. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.3</b></Level3> ={θηλυφόνον}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 9.18.2. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> the constellation [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Scorpio”, 4th-3rd c.BC(?): Cleostratus Poeta Philosophus 1, 4th-3rd c.BC: Aratus Epicus 85, 4th c.BC: Eudoxus Astronomus cited in 2nd c.BC: Hipparchus Astronomicus 1.2.20, 3rd c.BC: Eratosthenes Epicus “Καταστερισμοί” 7. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__V</b></Level2> an engine of war for discharging arrows, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-1st c.BC(?): Hero Mechanicus “Belopoeica” 74.6, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Marcellus” 15; σκορπίων σωλῆνες “IG” 22.1627.333. \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__VI</b></Level2> a stone, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.AD: Orphica “Lithica” 500, compare 494. \">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G4651","accentedUnicode":"σκορπίος","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G4650","matchingForm":"σκορπίζω","stepTransliteration":"skorpizō","gloss":"to scatter","_zh_tw_Gloss":"分散, 趕散","_es_Gloss":"esparcir","_zh_Gloss":"分散, 赶散"}],"shortDef":"scorpion","mediumDef":"<b>a scorpion,</b> a large insect, sometimes several inches in length, shaped somewhat like a crab and furnished with a tail terminating in a stinger from which it emits a dangerous poison, <ref='Luk.10.19; 11:12'>Lk. 10:19; 11:12</ref>; <ref='Rev.9.3, 5, 10'>Rev. 9:3, 5, 10</ref>*","stepGloss":"scorpion","stepTransliteration":"skorpios","count":5,"_es_Definition":"escorpión, alacrán","_zh_tw_Definition":"蝎子","_zh_Definition":"蝎子","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"con bọ cạp","_zh_tw_Gloss":"蠍子","_es_Gloss":"escorpión","_zh_Gloss":"蝎子"}]}